.container-color--dark
  section.section-article
    .row.align-center
      .columns.small-12.medium-10.large-8.text-center
        h1.headline-2.group.text-center How Shared Responsibility Works
        p Information security and compliance is always a shared responsibility among many partners. When you work with Datica we're sharing the responsibility of compliance and data protection with you. This also extends to our relationship with AWS. Our Business Associate Agreement with AWS defines the lines of risk between the two companies. This is also the case with the BAA you sign with us. See the diagram below to get a picture of where each parties responsibilities lie.
    .row.align-center
      .columns.small-12
        img.group src="https://images.contentful.com/189dvqdsjh46/1bottJswv0ASw8QOM66iqA/3be8a09da4cf9d64792341db89c8b70d/01-shared-response-aws-2x.png" alt="Explaining Shared Responsibility" /
    .row.align-center
      .columns.small-12.medium-6
        p Essentially AWS will take on the risk of securing the physical infrastructure. They ensure no one will run into a datacenter and run out the door with a server containing PHI. This is a key responsibility in the shared model. However, this doesn’t get you much in the way of HIPAA compliance.
    .row.align-center
      .columns.small-12.medium-9
        img.group src="https://images.contentful.com/189dvqdsjh46/5FlerlFow8smWSuYeS8Ews/e75d0ca0fbc5667a56cce363eee0d996/02-shared-response-aws-2x.png" alt="Explaining Shared Responsibility" /
    .row.align-center
      .columns.small-12.medium-6
        p Compliance is multi-faceted with many layers of responsibility. Without Datica, you'll be responsible for the entirety of compliance. From the cloud infrastructure layer to the application layer and beyond.
        p.group The only reason you would ever want to take this on is if you feel compliance a critical value you provide to your end user. Meaning, unless you're in the business of supplying compliance, this is not something you want to take on.
    .row.align-center
      .columns.small-12.medium-8
        img.group src="https://images.contentful.com/189dvqdsjh46/H0ZRYWKaK2GSMiEi4yasg/60f5c0d7d87d534415a3bcc7a242a1f8/03-shared-response-aws-2x.png" alt="Explaining Shared Responsibility" /
    .row.align-center
      .columns.small-12.medium-6
        p.group Beyond building compliance controls and mappings on top of AWS (as shown above) — you're still responsbile for the entirety of application level and administrative compliance.
    .row.align-center
      .columns.small-12.medium-8
        img.group src="https://images.contentful.com/189dvqdsjh46/1a2ghb7NiSqugqO28Yq4ic/0f873023970e176c4ac631c2ae607d9c/04-shared-response-aws-2x.png" alt="Explaining Shared Responsibility" /
    .row.align-center
      .columns.small-12.medium-6
        p When you add up all of the compliance responsibilities across the entire spectrum of the cloud, you start to see just how large it is. No one company should take on even half of this.
        p.group In the same way that you'll rely on AWS to secure the physical infrastructure in their datacenters, you should rely on Datica to deliver the 9/10ths of compliance required for HIPAA, HITRUST, GDPR, and more.

